Looking carefully at the `add` method and the test `testGetRangeBounds`, I can see the issue. The test adds an item with min outlier 8.5 and max outlier 9.5, then replaces the item at R1,C1 with new values. The new item has min outlier of 8.6 and max outlier of 9.6. Since the replaced item had the minimum value (8.5), the cached bounds don't get properly recalculated to find the new minimum, which is now 8.5 from the R2,C1 item.

The problem is in the `add` method. When we replace an item that was previously holding the minimum or maximum cached value, the code calls `updateBounds()` but that method only resets the cached values to `Double.NaN` without actually recalculating the true minimum and maximum across ALL items in the dataset.

Let me look more closely at the `updateBounds()` method:

```java
private void updateBounds() {
    this.minimumRangeValue = Double.NaN;
    this.minimumRangeValueRow = -1;
    this.minimumRangeValueColumn = -1;
    this.maximumRangeValue = Double.NaN;
    this.maximumRangeValueRow = -1;
    this.maximumRangeValueColumn = -1;
    this.rangeBounds = new Range(this.minimumRangeValue, this.maximumRangeValue);
}
```

Ah, I see! The `updateBounds()` method sets the cached values to NaN but never recalculates the actual min/max values by iterating through all the data. The `add` method then proceeds to only update the cached values based on the newly added item, but it doesn't consider that the new global min/max might come from a different item in the dataset.

The `updateBounds()` method should iterate through all items in the dataset to find the true min and max values, but it's incomplete. Let me check if there's an existing complete implementation somewhere:

Looking again at the test, the final assertion shows that after replacing the item that held the minimum value (8.5), the new range should be from 8.5 (from the remaining item) to 9.6 (from the new replacement item), giving Range(8.5, 9.6). But it's likely failing because the bounds calculation is wrong.

Let me fix the `updateBounds()` method to properly recalculate the bounds by iterating through all data:

